%N A325300 a(n) is the number of faces of the stepped pyramid with n levels described in A245092.
%C A325300 To calculate a(n) consider that levels greater than n do not exist.
%C A325300 The shape of the n-th level of the pyramid allows us to know if n is prime (see the Formula section).
%C A325300 For more information about the sequences that we can see in the pyramid see A262626.
%H A325300 Omar E. Pol, <a href="http://www.polprimos.com/imagenespub/polpyr05.jpg">Perspective view of the pyramid (first 16 levels)</a>
%F A325300 a(n) = A325301(n) - A325302(n) + 2 (Euler's formula).
%F A325300 a(n) = A323645(n) + 3.
%F A325300 a(n) = a(n-1) + 4 iff n is a prime > 3 (A215848).
%e A325300 For n = 1 the first level of the stepped pyramid (starting from the top) is a cube, and a cube has six faces, so a(1) = 6.
%Y A325300 Cf. A325301 (number of edges), A325302 (number of vertices).
